INSTALL — CUDA Batch Gaussian Blur
===================================

PREREQUISITES
-------------

All platforms require an NVIDIA GPU with CUDA compute capability >= 6.0.

Linux (Ubuntu 20.04 / 22.04)
-----------------------------

1. Install the CUDA Toolkit (includes nvcc and NPP):

     https://developer.nvidia.com/cuda-downloads

   Or via the package manager (replace 12-3 with your toolkit version):

     sudo apt-get install cuda-toolkit-12-3

2. Confirm nvcc is on your PATH:

     nvcc --version

3. Install Python 3 and NumPy (for test image generation only):

     sudo apt-get install python3 python3-pip
     pip3 install numpy

4. Build:

     cd <project-root>
     make

5. Verify the binary was created:

     ls bin/image_processor

6. Run:

     ./run.sh
   or
     ./bin/image_processor --input data/input --output data/output --mask 5


AWS / Google Cloud / Coursera Lab Environment
----------------------------------------------

CUDA Toolkit and NPP are typically pre-installed. Skip step 1 and proceed
from step 2.

If NPP libraries are missing, install them:

     sudo apt-get install libnpp-dev-12-3   # adjust version number


NOTES
-----

- The Makefile targets GPU architectures sm_60 through sm_89. If your GPU
  is older (Kepler/Maxwell) or newer (Hopper/Ada), add the appropriate
  -gencode flag to ARCH_FLAGS in the Makefile.

- If you see "error: NPP header not found", ensure the CUDA include path
  is set correctly. The default nvcc installation usually handles this
  automatically.

- Output directory is created automatically by run.sh. When calling the
  binary directly, create it first:

     mkdir -p data/output
